value.value: Deposition of cystine crystals in kidney tissue. Cystine crystals display a pathognomic hexagonal shape.
Accumulation of cystine in the liver.

definition.value: Cystine crystal accumulation activates Kupffer cells and secreted vasoactive substances cause vasoconstriction in microcirculation resulting in portal hypertension

value.value: The presence of cystine crystals in bone marrow cells as demonstrated in a fresh bone marrow aspiration sample.

Desmoid tumors are rare, locally aggressive, fibroblastic soft-tissue tumors that are characterized by infiltrative growth and tendency to recur. Desmoid tumors do not metastasize but can arise in any part of the body: extra-abdominal (appear in the head and neck, chest, extremities), and abdominal wall or intra-abdominal (originating in tissue that connects abdominal organs).
A segment of the jejunum that runs parallel to the normal jejunum and communicates with the jejunal lumen at one or both ends.
A full thickness tear or breakage of the myocardium of the left ventricle.
Multiple punctate (speckled, patchy spot-like) and/or curvilinear areas of gadolinium enhancement distributed around blood vessels in the pons.

definition.value: The lesions may extend into adjacent CNS structures, caudally to the medulla oblongata or the cervicothoracal spinal cord, rostrally to the midbrain, and even involve supratentorial regions such as the thalami, capsula interna, basal ganglia, corpus callosum and cerebral white matter. See Figure 1 of PMID:24028073.

value.value: Presence of one or more adult worms in the intestine as demonstrated by sonography or passage of a worm in the stool. On sonography, worms may appear as linear, echogenic structures within the intestines.
Demonstration of one or more worms in the scrotum. This finding can be appreciated by sonography, where echogenic, linear structures could be seen moving within the scrotum.
A small bowel tumor with adenomatous epithelium.

definition.value: Grossly and histologically, adenomas arising in the mucosa of the small intestine are similar to the adenomas found in the colon.

value.value: Mottling (spots or blotches with different shades) of the retinal pigment epithelium in the mother of the index patient. Retinal mottling may indicate a mosaic X-linked inactivation state in the mother.

A stretched conical-shaped structure found at the gallbladder neck with several linear echoes converging towards its tip. This finding is demonstrated by sonography and can indicate gallbladder volvulus.
Fistula between the gallbladder and the intestine.
Impaired ability to accurately measure or estimate time intervals.

definition.value: Common signs of dyschronometria are often generic to cerebellar ataxia, including a lack of spatial awareness, poor short term memory, and inability to keep track of time. For example, when asked to wait for thirty seconds, or tap every second that has gone by, those affected will be able to perform the task for a short time and then become derailed. This can result from a loss of focus, however, more often than not the individual affected can no longer tell what they are doing and they become disoriented. This often takes form in forgetting basic time keeping unless a timer is set, such as when cooking for example. Dyschronometria does not affect the 24-hour circadian rhythm, which is sustained by a different biological process.
History of recently intermittent breastfeeding an infant (i.e., on and off).
Recent on and off breastfeeding can be a risk factor for galactocele and breast abscess.
A benign, fluid-filled sac in the breast.
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance are well-defined and localized to a specific area.
Applies to an abnormality that displays ultiple indentations and/or elevations producing an irregular surface contour.

value.value: Applies to an abnormality with irregular, radiating, or spiky edges.

definition.value: A spiculated mass is a centrally dense lesion seen on mammography with sharp lines radiating from its margin. The spicules can vary greatly in length, from a few millimeters to several centimeters. In malignant lesions, spicules represent a mixture of tumor cells and fibrosis invading the normal tissue surrounding the lesion.
Applies to an abnormality whose distribution and appearance resembles series of a concentric circles or spirals.

value.value: Delta brushes are transient patterns characterised by a slow delta wave with superimposed fast activity.

definition.value: Delta brushes are the hallmark of the EEG of premature infants.

value.value: Fusion of the junction between the distal tibia, fibula and the talus.
he term given when a vertebral body has lost almost its entire height anteriorly and posteriorly, representing a very advanced compression fracture.
An abnormal gait caused by a rotational variation anywhere in the lower extremity that causes the foot to point inward, instead of pointing straight ahead or outward, when walking or running.

definition.value: The three major causes of pediatric in-toeing are metatarsus adductus, internal tibial torsion, and femoral anteversion.
A vibration felt upon palpation of a blood vessel over an extremity.
This feature can be due to an arteriovenous malformation.

value.value: The feet turn excessively outward when walking, caused by a rotational variation in the leg.
An abnormal separation between the talo-tibial joint.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against neuronal intermediate filament.
The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against dendritic spine scaffolding protein Drebrin.
The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against anti-lipoprotein lipase.
The presence of autoantibodies in the blood circulation that react against apoCII.
The presence of intracellular inclusion bodies (aggregates of stainable substances, usually proteins) in neurons that stain with eosin, a red or pink dye.
A characteristic smell said to resemble the odor of dirty socks.

definition.value: This feature is characteristic of isoveleric acidemia.

value.value: The presence of autoantibodies (immunoglobulins) in the blood circulation that react against acetylcholine receptor.

definition.value: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (AChR) are ligand-gated cation channels that are present throughout the nervous system. The muscle AChR mediates transmission at the neuromuscular junction; antibodies against the muscle AChR are the cause of myasthenia gravis. The ganglionic (alpha 3-type) neuronal AChR mediates fast synaptic transmission in sympathetic, parasympathetic, and enteric autonomic ganglia. Impaired cholinergic ganglionic synaptic transmission is one important cause of autonomic failure.
Applies to an abnormality that is located on hair shafts.

label.value: Prolonged use of tightly fitting footwear

value.value: History of use of tightly fitting shoes for a long period of time.

definition.value: This may be a risk factor for tinea pedis.

value.value: Applies to a sign or symptom that is provoked or brought about ingestion of high quantities of protein.

definition.value: Metabolic triggers for late-onset urea cycle disorders include excessive protein intake.

value.value: An abnormally increased thickness of a leaflet of the tricuspid valve.
Abnormal shifting of the anterior fontanelle fropm its normal central position.

definition.value: This feature can be related to an abnormality of the cranial sutures, mostly craniosynostosis.

value.value: Accumulation of cerebral spinal fluid in the subdural space.

Incus ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the incus, which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles).
A tendency to reject a variety of foods and/or to eat a restricted range of foods.
Dyskinesis is used to describe ventricular muscle segments that bulge outside the left ventricular cavity during systole, as opposed to contracting inwards with the rest of the segments.
A longitudinal red band extending from the proximal nail fold or lunula to the distal nail plate.

definition.value: Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by exposure to sunlight.
Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by exposure to heat (high ambient temperatures).

value.value: Applied to a sign or symptom that is made worse by excessive sweating.

definition.value: High temperatures, high humidity, excessive sweating can exacerbate cutaneous wounds.

value.value: The accumulation of a significant amount of exudate in the pleural space, accompanied by the presence of malignant cells or tumour tissue.

label.value: Inappropriately low urine osmolality following challenge

value.value: In diabetes insipidus, affected individuals produce large quantities of dilute urine. In nephrogenic DI, the kidneys do not respond to vasopressin. In a water deprivation test or with administration of exogenous vasopressin, the osmolaltiy of the urine does not increase as normally.

label.value: Reduced urine retrahydrocortisol plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone ratio

value.value: Abnormally low ratio of tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone (THE).

definition.value: In cortisone reductase deficiency-2, the ratio of tetrahydrocortisol (THF) plus 5-alpha-THF to tetrahydrocortisone (THE), which in CORTRD patients is typically less than 0.1 (reference range, 0.7 to 1.2).
